<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Hanging Systems vs Freestanding Stands</h2>

  <h3>Hanging Systems</h3>
  <p>
    These suspend lights from a shelf or frame above. They are usually the most flexible option and work especially well with wire shelving.
  </p>

  <h3>Freestanding Stands</h3>
  <p>
    These hold lights independently of shelves. They are useful when you do not have a structure to hang from but can take up more space.
  </p>

  <p>
    For most seed-starting shelves, hanging systems are simpler and more adaptable.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What to Look For in a Grow Light Stand</h2>

  <h3>1. Easy Height Adjustment</h3>
  <p>
    Lights need to move frequently. A stand that allows quick adjustment is much easier to use.
  </p>

  <h3>2. Stability</h3>
  <p>
    Lights should stay level and secure without shifting or tilting.
  </p>

  <h3>3. Compatibility with Shelves</h3>
  <p>
    The system should integrate cleanly with your shelf setup without awkward modifications.
  </p>

  <h3>4. Enough Range for Growth</h3>
  <p>
    The stand should allow lights to move from very close to seedlings up to a higher position as plants grow.
  </p>

  <h3>5. Simplicity</h3>
  <p>
    The easier the system is to use, the more consistently you will adjust it properly.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Adjustability Matters So Much</h2>

  <p>
    Seedlings need light close above them to avoid becoming leggy. As they grow, the light must move upward to maintain the correct distance.
  </p>

  <p>
    A fixed light setup quickly becomes ineffective. An adjustable system keeps light levels consistent without requiring constant repositioning of trays.
  </p>

  <p>
    For most gardeners, adjustability is more important than the type of stand itself.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Overlook</h2>

  <p>
    One common issue is setting lights too high and leaving them there. Even a good stand does not help if it is not adjusted regularly.
  </p>

  <p>
    Another issue is overcrowding shelves. As plants grow, they need both vertical and horizontal space, and the light setup needs to accommodate that.
  </p>

